The definition of `HasLaw f L M` is `∀ A, M (f⁻¹' A) = L(A)`.
So, we need to show `∀ A, (WignerMeasure μ ν n) {ω | (fun ω => ω ⟨(min i j, max i j), by exact min_le_max⟩) ω ∈ A} = μ A`.
The left side is `(WignerMeasure μ ν n) {ω | ω ⟨(min i j, max i j), by exact min_le_max⟩ ∈ A}`.
By the definition of `WignerMeasure`, this is `Measure.pi (fun p ↦ if p.val.1 = p.val.2 then ν else μ) {ω | ω ⟨(min i j, max i j), by exact min_le_max⟩ ∈ A}`.
This is equal to `μ A` because `⟨(min i j, max i j), by exact min_le_max⟩` is an off-diagonal index (since `i ≠ j` implies `min i j ≠ max i j`), so the `i`-th coordinate (where `i` is the index in `WignerSpace n`) has law `μ`.

